{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537847"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:21:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:21:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16073"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16073"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.05,0.11,0.1,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8764"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110480"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8764"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16073"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92744"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"3514"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6364"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34404"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39548"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43603"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110480"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for routine antenatal care at 28 weeks gestation. This is her first pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and takes pregnancy multivitamins. Her booking body mass index was 27 kg/m\u00b2. Her pregnancy has been uncomplicated to date with normal morphology scan and she has been receiving shared care between her General Practitioner and midwife.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her fundal height measures 29 cm. Her oral glucose tolerance test reveals: fasting glucose 5.5 mmol/L (\u0026lt;5.3), 1-hour glucose 11.2 mmol/L (\u0026lt;10.6), 2-hour glucose 9.1 mmol/L (\u0026lt;9.0). After two weeks of dietary modification and blood glucose monitoring, her morning pre-prandial readings remain consistently above 7.0 mmol/L.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate model of care?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transfer to midwifery-led care","Transfer to endocrinology-led care","Continue General Practice shared care","Transfer to diabetes educator-led care","Transfer to obstetric-led care with endocrinology input"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has been diagnosed with gestational diabetes mellitus (GDM) based on her oral glucose tolerance test results, with all three values above the diagnostic thresholds. Despite dietary modification, her blood glucose levels remain elevated, indicating the need for insulin therapy. This represents a significant change in her pregnancy risk profile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to obstetric-led care with endocrinology input\u003C/strong\u003E is most appropriate as insulin-requiring GDM increases the risk of adverse pregnancy outcomes including macrosomia, shoulder dystocia, and caesarean delivery. These women require regular obstetric review for fetal growth monitoring and delivery planning, alongside specialist input for insulin management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue General Practice shared care\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate given the complexity of managing insulin therapy and monitoring for complications of GDM. While GPs can manage diet-controlled GDM, insulin therapy requires specialist oversight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to midwifery-led care\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as this pregnancy no longer meets the criteria for low-risk care. Midwifery-led care is suitable for uncomplicated pregnancies without medical or obstetric risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to endocrinology-led care\u003C/strong\u003E alone would not address the obstetric complications associated with GDM. While endocrinology input is important for insulin management, the primary care should be obstetric-led.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to diabetes educator-led care\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient as diabetes educators, while vital for patient education and support, do not have the expertise to manage the obstetric complications of GDM.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that in rural or remote settings where specialist services may be limited, GP Obstetricians can provide care for higher-risk pregnancies like this one. In such cases, the patient would still receive obstetric-led care, but it would be provided by a GP Obstetrician, potentially with telehealth support from endocrinology and tertiary obstetric services. The patient would still be required to birth in a center with appropriate obstetric support given the increased risks associated with insulin-requiring GDM.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gestational diabetes requiring insulin therapy is an indication for transition to obstetric-led care.","Women with gestational diabetes requiring insulin have increased risks of macrosomia, shoulder dystocia, and caesarean delivery.","Shared care between obstetrics and diabetes specialists is optimal for insulin-requiring gestational diabetes."],"references":["Australian Institute of Health and Welfare (AIHW). Maternity models of care: What do maternity models of care look like? Major model category [Internet]. Canberra: AIHW; 2023 [cited 2024 Nov 22]. Available from: https://www.aihw.gov.au/reports/mothers-babies/maternity-models-of-care/contents/what-do-maternity-models-of-care-look-like/major-model-category","Australasian Diabetes in Pregnancy Society (ADIPS). 2024 Gestational Diabetes Mellitus (GDM) Recommendations Summary. ADIPS; 2024. Available from: https://mcusercontent.com/098b0bb2d5b5714dc366129f4/files/932da0a0-5f10-8de2-8292-db3aef70496f/ADIPS_2024_GDM_Recommendations_Summary.pdf","Sweeting A, Hare MJ, de Jersey SJ, Shub AL, Zinga J, Foged C, Hall RM, Wong T, Simmons D. Australasian Diabetes in Pregnancy Society (ADIPS) 2025 consensus recommendations for the screening, diagnosis and classification of gestational diabetes. Med J Aust. 2025 Jun 22. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40544364/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92744"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16073"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92744"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-31T11:55:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-31T11:55:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8764"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110480"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66